(17, 'Rihanna mispronounces Radhika Merchant\'s name at Ambanis\' gala', 'rihanna-mispronounces-radhika-merchants-name-at-ambanis-gala', 'Pop icon Rihanna was recently in Jamnagar to perform at the Ambanis\' bash. At the event', '<h3>In Short</h3><ul><li>Rihanna mispronounced Radhika Merchant\'s name at her Jamnagar performance</li><li>Rihanna was performing for the first time in India</li><li>The pop icon performed to a number of hit songs at the bash</li></ul>', 1, '2024-03-04 00:23:30', '2024-03-04 00:23:30'),
(19, 'Mukesh Ambani\'s son Anant\'s wedding: A grand affair with global celebrities in attendance', 'mukesh-ambanis-son-anants-wedding-a-grand-affair-with-global-celebrities-in-attendance', 'he three-day pre-wedding celebrations of Reliance chairman Mukesh Ambani and wife Nita’s youngest son, Anant, to Radhika Merchant saw a veritable roll-call of high-wattage personalities touch down at Jamnagar.', '<p>body content</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-03-04 00:23:50', '2024-03-04 00:23:50'),
(20, 'The Zuckerbergs were all about \'loud luxury\' at the Ambani family\'s opulent pre-wedding festivities in India', 'the-zuckerbergs-were-all-about-loud-luxury-at-the-ambani-familys-opulent-pre-wedding-festivities-in-india', 'Lauren Edmonds', '<h2><strong>The Zuckerbergs tend to use subtle symbols of wealth but paid top dollar for their bold pre-wedding ensembles</strong></h2><p>Fans familiar with Zuckerberg and Chan know they have a propensity toward quiet luxury. The trend is difficult to spot, but one example is <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/mark-zuckerberg-favorite-tshirt-2017-7?utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_source=yahoo.com\">Zuckerberg\'s habit of wearing basic gray t-shirts that cost between $300 and $400.</a></p><p>However, the couple\'s weekend in India was full of loud luxury.</p><p>Zuckerberg and Chan began the celebrations on Friday by wearing two black outfits designed by Alexander McQueen, <a href=\"https://www.vogue.in/gallery/at-the-pre-wedding-events-of-radhika-merchant-and-anant-ambani-who-wore-what-from-alia-bhatt-to-deepika-padukone\">according to Vogue</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Zuckerberg\'s black shirt and matching pants were paired with the Alexander McQueen firefly-themed jacket, which is <a href=\"https://www.alexandermcqueen.com/en-us/pr/dragonfly-applique-single-breasted-jacket-774912QVAAA1000.html\">priced at $7,000.</a> Chan\'s floor-length gown features bold gold floral accents and is <a href=\"https://www.alexandermcqueen.com/en-us/pr/gold-rose-embroidery-evening-dress-790979QEAAA1000.html%20\">available for $15,000.</a></p><p>The couple kicked their style up a notch the next day when Zuckerberg wore a shimmering tigress-themed shirt designed by Rahul Mishra, who <a href=\"https://www.instagram.com/p/C4DaD-8hxkc/?hl=en&amp;img_index=5\">shared photos</a> on his Instagram account.</p><p>The <a href=\"https://rahulmishra.in/products/le-soleil-sundarbans-short-shirt\">organza shirt</a> is available on Mishra\'s website, but customers must request the official cost — suggesting a hefty price tag.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>That night, both Zuckerberg and Chan wore different outfits designed by Mishra, who shared photos of the occasion on his Instagram Stories. Chan wore a two-piece outfit decorated with nature-themed adornments like two gold birds. Zuckerberg\'s outfit was also modeled after wildlife with flowers and other foliage designs.</p>', 1, '2024-03-04 00:23:54', '2024-03-04 00:23:54'),
(21, 'Union Minister Dr Jitendra Singh launches the theme for National Science Day \'Indigenous Technologies for Viksit Bharat\'', 'union-minister-dr-jitendra-singh-launches-the-theme-for-national-science-day-indigenous-technologies-for-viksit-bharat', 'Indigenous Technologies for Viksit Bharat', '<p>Union Minister of State (Independent Charge) Science &amp; Technology; MoS PMO, Personnel, Public Grievances, Pensions, Atomic Energy and Space, Dr Jitendra Singh today released the theme for the \"National Science Day 2024\", titled \"Indigenous Technologies for Viksit Bharat\".</p><p>The NSD Theme for this year’s celebration reflects a strategic focus on promoting public appreciation for Science, Technology and Innovation and accomplishments of Indian scientists to address challenges through home-grown technologies for over-all well-being.</p>', 1, '2024-03-04 00:23:57', '2024-03-04 00:23:57'),
(22, 'Nita Ambani performs at Anant Ambani-Radhika Merchant pre-wedding festivities. Watch In a video of the performance shared on X (formerly Twitter), Nita Ambani could', 'nita-ambani-performs-at-anant-ambani-radhika-merchant-pre-wedding-festivities-watch-in-a-video-of-the-performance-shared-on-x-formerly-twitter-nita-ambani-could', 'Nita Ambani performs at the Anant Ambani-Radhika Merchant pre-wedding activities. (Image credit: Screengrab from video posted on Twitter/ANI).', '<p>Founder and Chairperson of Reliance Foundation Nita Ambani graced the pre-wedding festivities for Anant Ambani and Radhika Merchant and performed to a rendition of&nbsp;the Vishwambhari Stuti, a hymn dedicated to Maa Ambe.</p><p>In a video of the performance shared on X (formerly Twitter), Nita Ambani could be seen pouring her heart and soul into the performance and invoking the diving blessings for Anant Ambani and Radhika Merchant\'s journey of togetherness.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The performance was led by music directors Ajay-Atul and singer Shreya Ghoshal, with the choreography done by Vaibhavi Merchant. Nita Ambani\'s outfit was designed by Manish Malhotra while the other dancers wore costumes designed by Ashley Rebello.</p><p>Also, Nita Ambani extended her dedication to her granddaughters, Aadiya Shakti and Veda and her performance at the pre-wedding festivities served as a tribute to the spirit and vitality of all young girls.</p><p>READ MORE&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-03-04 00:24:17', '2024-03-04 00:24:17'),
(24, 'The end of 0% interest rates: what it means for software engineering practices', 'the-end-of-0-interest-rates-what-it-means-for-software-engineering-practices', 'Could we see monoliths favored over microservices, full-stack tools over platform specific ones and pragmatic, simpler architecture as a response to 10+ years of 0% interest rates ending?', '<p><i>👋 Hi, this is Gergely with a subscriber-only issue of the Pragmatic Engineer Newsletter. In every issue, I cover challenges at Big Tech and startups through the lens of engineering managers and senior engineers. To get articles like this in your inbox, every week, subscribe:</i></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Subscribe</p><p>This article is part 4 in a 4-part series on the end of 0% interest rates. Other issues cover:</p><ul><li><a href=\"https://newsletter.pragmaticengineer.com/p/zirp\"><strong>What it means for startups and the tech industry</strong></a><strong> </strong>(Part 1.) More pressure to achieve profitability, less venture capital funding, Big Tech gets bigger, and bootstrapping more common.</li><li><a href=\"https://newsletter.pragmaticengineer.com/p/zirp-software-engineers\"><strong>What it means for software engineers</strong></a><strong> </strong>(Part 2.) A tougher job market, harder to negotiate offers, slower career growth, and higher performance expectations.</li><li><a href=\"https://newsletter.pragmaticengineer.com/p/zirp-engineering-managers\"><strong>What it means for engineering managers</strong></a><strong> </strong>(Part 3.)<strong> </strong>Fewer EMs, more responsibilities for the rest, the rise of the tech lead role, and an opportunity to build more cohesive teams due to lower attrition.</li><li><a href=\"https://newsletter.pragmaticengineer.com/p/zirp-engineering-practices\"><strong>What it means for software engineering practices</strong></a><strong> </strong>(Part 4, this one.) Monoliths over microservices, more shifting left of responsiblities and pragmatic, simpler architecture.</li></ul><p><i>Before we start: The ebook version of my book, </i><a href=\"https://www.engguidebook.com/\"><i>The Software Engineer’s Guidebook</i></a><i> is (finally!) available on all major ebook platforms. </i><a href=\"https://www.engguidebook.com/#buy\"><i><strong>Get it here.</strong></i></a><i> You can grab it on Kindle, as DRM-free ePub/PDF and on </i><a href=\"https://geni.us/engguidebook-choice\"><i>other popular ebook marketplaces</i></a><i>. If you’re wondering what it’s like: here’s </i><a href=\"https://www.sandordargo.com/blog/2024/02/17/the-software-engineers-guidebook-by-orosz-gergely\"><i>a recent book review</i></a><i> from Sandor Dargo, Senior Engineer at Spotify.</i></p><p>A long period of zero percent interest rate policies (ZIRP) recently ended, after lasting nearly a decade and a half since the global financial crisis of 2007-2008. That ZIRP period also coincided with the smartphone and cloud computing revolutions. So far in this series analyzing what today’s post-ZIRP era means for tech workers, we’ve covered <a href=\"https://newsletter.pragmaticengineer.com/p/zirp\">what a 0% rate era is, why it matters for tech</a>, and also:</p><ul><li><a href=\"https://newsletter.pragmaticengineer.com/p/zirp\"><strong>What it means for startups and the tech industry.</strong></a> More pressure to achieve profitability, less venture capital funding, Big Tech gets bigger, and bootstrapping more common.</li><li><a href=\"https://newsletter.pragmaticengineer.com/p/zirp-software-engineers\"><strong>What it means for software engineers.</strong></a> A tougher job market, harder to negotiate offers, slower career growth, and higher performance expectations.</li><li><a href=\"https://newsletter.pragmaticengineer.com/p/zirp-engineering-managers\"><strong>What it means for engineering managers.</strong></a><strong> </strong>Fewer EMs, more responsibilities for the rest, the rise of the tech lead role, and an opportunity to build more cohesive teams due to lower attrition.</li></ul><p>We wrap up this important topic with a focus on software engineering practices, and what to expect in how most companies build software in future. Today, we cover:</p><ol><li><strong>Monoliths favored over microservices? </strong>Microservices are a great tool to prepare for hypergrowth in headcount. But do we even need them when growth is slow, or perhaps even negative?</li><li><strong>Full-stack and cross-platform push. </strong>Engineering teams where with full-stack engineers, using cross-platform frameworks get the same stuff done with fewer people, with slightly less polish. That “less polish” is harder to notice: but the smaller team size means faster iteration and lower overall cost that are both harder to ignore.</li><li><strong>Pragmatic, simpler architecture. </strong>During ZIRP, it made sense to solve problems the engineering team doesn’t yet have, but will have in 6-12 months. With ZIRP behind us, this could be a more wasteful approach. Why not solve architecture issues <i>when teams feel the pain</i> of the current architecture slowing things down too much?</li><li><strong>More responsibilities “shift left.” </strong>Developers end up taking on more responsibilities on DevOps, security, infra and platforms. All this comes with better tools to be able to manage all this – and, at larger companies, centralized security and platform teams supporting engineers.</li><li><strong>Buy vs build vs use open source. </strong>Building non-core tools in-house will make much less sense, when looking at the numbers – especially if <a href=\"https://newsletter.pragmaticengineer.com/p/the-pulse-75\">Section 174 tax changes stay in place</a>. A more common question will be to buy from a vendor, or operate an open source solution instead?</li><li><strong>Commercial backing for the most popular open source projects. </strong>The open source field will almost certainly shift: community funded open source projects could see fewer companies contributing, while some of the widely used – and well-supported – open source projects will likely see licenses become more restrictive.</li><li><strong>Other industry observations. </strong>Less focus whether engineers enjoy working on a project; serving sales teams becomes more important; less tech debt and more business priorities focus, amongst others.</li></ol><h2>1. Monoliths favored over microservices?</h2><p>&nbsp;</p><p>One of the 2010s’ biggest architectural innovations was microservices. The first conference talks to mention this term were in 2012-2013, and Martin Fowler and James Lewis wrote <a href=\"https://martinfowler.com/articles/microservices.html\">an in-depth guide about the new approach in 2014.</a></p><p>Uber was a well-known scaleup at the time which adopted and popularized microservices, extensively <a href=\"https://www.uber.com/en-NL/blog/service-oriented-architecture\">writing about it</a> in engineering blogs, and giving talks; for example, “<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kb-m2fasdDY\">What I wish I had known before scaling Uber to 1,000 services</a>” by Matt Ranney.)</p><p>Others followed and created thousands of microservices. In the UK, neobank Monzo embarked on this journey in 2015, and cofounder Tom Blomfield kicked it off with this Slack message:</p><figure class=\"image\"><picture><source srcset=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd1eed334-3b59-4c35-bf53-55010e2aa0f1_1218x534.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd1eed334-3b59-4c35-bf53-55010e2aa0f1_1218x534.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd1eed334-3b59-4c35-bf53-55010e2aa0f1_1218x534.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd1eed334-3b59-4c35-bf53-55010e2aa0f1_1218x534.png 1456w\" type=\"image/webp\" sizes=\"100vw\"><img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd1eed334-3b59-4c35-bf53-55010e2aa0f1_1218x534.png\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd1eed334-3b59-4c35-bf53-55010e2aa0f1_1218x534.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd1eed334-3b59-4c35-bf53-55010e2aa0f1_1218x534.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd1eed334-3b59-4c35-bf53-55010e2aa0f1_1218x534.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd1eed334-3b59-4c35-bf53-55010e2aa0f1_1218x534.png 1456w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1218\" height=\"534\"></picture></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p><i>The first step towards thousands of microservices at Monzo. Source: </i><a href=\"https://www.infoq.com/presentations/banking-thousands-microservices-2023/\"><i>Banking on Thousands of Microservices, InfoQ</i></a></p><p>In 2024, we know the “???” in his message means “wait a long, long time.” It took Monzo 8 years to get from “2. Microservices,” to “4. Profit,” when it enjoyed its first month in the black <a href=\"https://www.cnbc.com/2023/05/31/british-digital-bank-monzo-hits-profitability-for-first-time.html\">in May 2023</a>, after Blomfield had left the company.</p><p>Microservices have been a Band-Aid for hypergrowth, and it’s unclear if they have uses beyond this. I was at Uber during the rapid growth of services, and their subsequent “taming,” so I have thoughts about the good and bad of microservices, and why Uber was better off for using them when it did.</p>', 1, '2024-03-04 00:25:09', '2024-03-04 00:25:09'),
(28, 'ASUS ROG Strix SCAR 16 2024 Review: Performance Powerhouse', 'asus-rog-strix-scar-16-2024-review-performance-powerhouse', 'ASUS ROG Strix SCAR 16 2024 Review: Performance Powerhouse', '<p><br><a href=\"https://www.digit.in/author/manish-rajesh/\"><img src=\"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/ebd1b0fca9fc7a821d6ce9b71597a853?s=70&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g\" alt=\"Manish Rajesh\" srcset=\"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/ebd1b0fca9fc7a821d6ce9b71597a853?s=140&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g 2x\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"70\" height=\"70\">MANISH RAJESH</a></p><p>03 MAR 2024 21:31</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>VERDICT:</strong></p><p>In conclusion, the ASUS ROG Strix Scar 16 is a game-changer, delivering desktop-level performance in a 16-inch laptop form factor. It’s a powerhouse that keeps up with the Scar legacy, featuring the most potent hardware in a premium chassis with a jaw-dropping display. While the range starts at ₹2,89,990, the variant we reviewed comes in at ₹3,29,990. If you’re serious about gaming and want a show-stopping experience, the SCAR 16 is worth every penny.</p><p>The ASUS ROG series has a legacy of delivering powerful gaming laptops, and the ROG Strix SCAR 16 is the latest addition to the powerhouse SCAR lineup. We had the opportunity to test the SCAR 18 during the Zero1 Awards last December and were quite impressed; it snagged the runner up position. On paper, with the hardware this laptop is packing, and its enticing price point (even at Rs 3.3 lakhs), this could just be the laptop for gamers looking to replace their gaming desktops.</p><h2><strong>ASUS ROG Strix SCAR 16 Specs at a glance</strong></h2><p><strong>Processor</strong>: Intel Core i9-14900HX<br><strong>GPU</strong>: NVIDIA GeForce RTX 4090<br><strong>VRAM</strong>: 16GB<br><strong>TGP</strong>: 175W<br><strong>RAM</strong>: 16GB DDR5-5600<br><strong>Storage</strong>: 2TB PCIe 4.0 NVMe M.2 SSD<br><strong>Display</strong>: 16-inch, QHD+ (2560×1600), 240Hz<br><strong>Price</strong>: Rs 3,29,990</p><h2><strong>ASUS ROG Strix SCAR 16 Gaming Performance</strong></h2><p>There’s no denying it, the SCAR 16 is an absolute beast, boasting a 14th Gen Intel Core i9 processor and an NVIDIA RTX 4090 GPU with a TGP of 175W. This is the highest allowed TGP by NVIDIA meaning we’re talking desktop-class performance packed into this 16-inch chassis. In our review unit, we had 32GB of RAM and 2TB of internal storage for all those massive game files. Real-world gaming performance is mind-blowing, delivering great frame rates at native QHD+ resolutions. Note that we run all of our real-world gaming benchmarks at 1080p to keep the playing field even so to speak.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><a href=\"https://static.digit.in/3DMark-5.png\"><img src=\"https://static.digit.in/3DMark-5-1024x576.png\" alt=\"ROG Strix SCAR 16\" srcset=\"https://static.digit.in/3DMark-5-1024x576.png 1024w, https://static.digit.in/3DMark-5-300x169.png 300w, https://static.digit.in/3DMark-5-768x432.png 768w, https://static.digit.in/3DMark-5-1536x864.png 1536w, https://static.digit.in/3DMark-5-2048x1152.png 2048w, https://static.digit.in/3DMark-5-267x150.png 267w, https://static.digit.in/3DMark-5-100x56.png 100w, https://static.digit.in/3DMark-5-622x350.png 622w, https://static.digit.in/3DMark-5-788x443.png 788w, https://static.digit.in/3DMark-5-599x337.png 599w, https://static.digit.in/3DMark-5-150x84.png 150w, https://static.digit.in/3DMark-5.png 1920w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1024\" height=\"576\"></a></p><p>Starting things off with the synthetic gaming benchmarks, for which we use 3DMark. We have Speed Way, Time Spy, Fire Strike and Port Royal to test DirectX 12, DirectX 11 and DXR performance respectively. As you can see, these are great scores across the board.</p><p>Synthetic benchmarks mean nothing if the laptop doesn’t perform when it comes to real-world gaming. Fortunately, the ROG Strix SCAR 16 absolutely demolishes our real-world gaming benchmarks, coming very close to our highest recorded scores to date. The numbers speak for themselves.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:204/115;\" src=\"https://static.digit.in/1-14-1024x576.png\" alt=\"ROG Strix SCAR 16\" srcset=\"https://static.digit.in/1-14-1024x576.png 1024w, https://static.digit.in/1-14-300x169.png 300w, https://static.digit.in/1-14-768x432.png 768w, https://static.digit.in/1-14-1536x864.png 1536w, https://static.digit.in/1-14-2048x1152.png 2048w, https://static.digit.in/1-14-267x150.png 267w, https://static.digit.in/1-14-100x56.png 100w, https://static.digit.in/1-14-622x350.png 622w, https://static.digit.in/1-14-788x443.png 788w, https://static.digit.in/1-14-599x337.png 599w, https://static.digit.in/1-14-150x84.png 150w, https://static.digit.in/1-14.png 1920w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"204\" height=\"115\"></figure><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:204/115;\" src=\"https://static.digit.in/2-15-1024x576.png\" alt=\"ROG Strix SCAR 16\" srcset=\"https://static.digit.in/2-15-1024x576.png 1024w, https://static.digit.in/2-15-300x169.png 300w, https://static.digit.in/2-15-768x432.png 768w, https://static.digit.in/2-15-1536x864.png 1536w, https://static.digit.in/2-15-2048x1152.png 2048w, https://static.digit.in/2-15-267x150.png 267w, https://static.digit.in/2-15-100x56.png 100w, https://static.digit.in/2-15-622x350.png 622w, https://static.digit.in/2-15-788x443.png 788w, https://static.digit.in/2-15-599x337.png 599w, https://static.digit.in/2-15-150x84.png 150w, https://static.digit.in/2-15.png 1920w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"204\" height=\"115\"></figure><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:204/115;\" src=\"https://static.digit.in/3-10-1024x576.png\" alt=\"ROG Strix SCAR 16\" srcset=\"https://static.digit.in/3-10-1024x576.png 1024w, https://static.digit.in/3-10-300x169.png 300w, https://static.digit.in/3-10-768x432.png 768w, https://static.digit.in/3-10-1536x864.png 1536w, https://static.digit.in/3-10-2048x1152.png 2048w, https://static.digit.in/3-10-267x150.png 267w, https://static.digit.in/3-10-100x56.png 100w, https://static.digit.in/3-10-622x350.png 622w, https://static.digit.in/3-10-788x443.png 788w, https://static.digit.in/3-10-599x337.png 599w, https://static.digit.in/3-10-150x84.png 150w, https://static.digit.in/3-10.png 1920w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"204\" height=\"115\"></figure><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:311/175;\" src=\"https://static.digit.in/4-13-1024x576.png\" alt=\"ROG Strix SCAR 16\" srcset=\"https://static.digit.in/4-13-1024x576.png 1024w, https://static.digit.in/4-13-300x169.png 300w, https://static.digit.in/4-13-768x432.png 768w, https://static.digit.in/4-13-1536x864.png 1536w, https://static.digit.in/4-13-2048x1152.png 2048w, https://static.digit.in/4-13-267x150.png 267w, https://static.digit.in/4-13-100x56.png 100w, https://static.digit.in/4-13-622x350.png 622w, https://static.digit.in/4-13-788x443.png 788w, https://static.digit.in/4-13-599x337.png 599w, https://static.digit.in/4-13-150x84.png 150w, https://static.digit.in/4-13.png 1920w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"311\" height=\"175\"></figure><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:311/175;\" src=\"https://static.digit.in/5-10-1024x576.png\" alt=\"ROG Strix SCAR 16\" srcset=\"https://static.digit.in/5-10-1024x576.png 1024w, https://static.digit.in/5-10-300x169.png 300w, https://static.digit.in/5-10-768x432.png 768w, https://static.digit.in/5-10-1536x864.png 1536w, https://static.digit.in/5-10-2048x1152.png 2048w, https://static.digit.in/5-10-267x150.png 267w, https://static.digit.in/5-10-100x56.png 100w, https://static.digit.in/5-10-622x350.png 622w, https://static.digit.in/5-10-788x443.png 788w, https://static.digit.in/5-10-599x337.png 599w, https://static.digit.in/5-10-150x84.png 150w, https://static.digit.in/5-10.png 1920w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"311\" height=\"175\"></figure><p>Of course, the laptop also comes with a 14th gen Intel processor, and while we do have Ultra processors in the market, we’re still waiting on Ultra processor gaming laptops. We compared the Intel Core i9-14900HX in the ROG Strix SCAR 16 to the Intel Core i9-13980HX in the MSI Raider GE78 HX just to see how much of a difference in performance there is between the two.</p><p><a href=\"https://static.digit.in/Processor-and-Productivity.png\"><img src=\"https://static.digit.in/Processor-and-Productivity-1024x634.png\" alt=\"ROG Strix SCAR 16\" srcset=\"https://static.digit.in/Processor-and-Productivity-1024x634.png 1024w, https://static.digit.in/Processor-and-Productivity-300x186.png 300w, https://static.digit.in/Processor-and-Productivity-768x475.png 768w, https://static.digit.in/Processor-and-Productivity-1536x950.png 1536w, https://static.digit.in/Processor-and-Productivity-2048x1267.png 2048w, https://static.digit.in/Processor-and-Productivity-242x150.png 242w, https://static.digit.in/Processor-and-Productivity-100x62.png 100w, https://static.digit.in/Processor-and-Productivity-566x350.png 566w, https://static.digit.in/Processor-and-Productivity-788x487.png 788w, https://static.digit.in/Processor-and-Productivity-600x371.png 600w, https://static.digit.in/Processor-and-Productivity-150x93.png 150w, https://static.digit.in/Processor-and-Productivity.png 1348w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1024\" height=\"634\"></a></p><p>Turns out, not a lot. The difference is almost negligible in most scores with the newer 14th gen processor inching slightly ahead in single-core performance.</p><p>And that’s not even the best part. There’s barely any thermal throttling, thanks to ASUS’s Intelligent Cooling technology.</p><p>No seriously, this thing runs <i>cool</i>. Even after hours of gaming. Recording heat at our usual spots, we saw peak surface temps of just 38 degrees Celsius with the average surface temp rounding out to around 25 degrees. The only laptop that scored higher than the SCAR 16 on thermal throttling is the SCAR 18, but even that had higher surface temps than the SCAR 16.</p><h2><strong>Display</strong></h2><p>The display is easily one of the best things the SCAR 16 has going for it. The 16-inch Quad HD+ (2560x1600p) ROG Nebula HDR display comes with a refresh rate of 240Hz. It’s got vibrant colours, inky blacks, and buttery smooth visuals. The mini LEDs enable better local dimming, and with 100% sRGB and DCI-P3 colour gamut coverage, plus Dolby Vision compliance, this is one of the best gaming displays you can find on a gaming laptop.&nbsp;</p><p><a href=\"https://static.digit.in/h732.png\"><img src=\"https://static.digit.in/h732-1024x1024.png\" alt=\"ASUS ROG Strix SCAR 16\" srcset=\"https://static.digit.in/h732-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://static.digit.in/h732-300x300.png 300w, https://static.digit.in/h732-150x150.png 150w, https://static.digit.in/h732-768x768.png 768w, https://static.digit.in/h732-1536x1536.png 1536w, https://static.digit.in/h732-2048x2048.png 2048w, https://static.digit.in/h732-100x100.png 100w, https://static.digit.in/h732-350x350.png 350w, https://static.digit.in/h732-788x788.png 788w, https://static.digit.in/h732-600x600.png 600w, https://static.digit.in/h732-96x96.png 96w, https://static.digit.in/h732.png 732w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1024\" height=\"1024\"></a></p><h2><strong>ASUS ROG Strix SCAR 16 Build &amp; Design</strong></h2><p>Moving on to the design, the Scar 16 screams gamer, but not in a tacky way. The aluminium and plastic construction makes it sturdy with close to zero flex. The RGB LED strips surrounding the rear and side vents light up the Scar in striking colours using the Aura Sync software. However, it isn’t the most portable laptop at almost 3 kg.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:632/632;\" src=\"https://static.digit.in/6-11-1024x1024.png\" alt=\"ASUS ROG Strix SCAR 16\" srcset=\"https://static.digit.in/6-11-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://static.digit.in/6-11-300x300.png 300w, https://static.digit.in/6-11-150x150.png 150w, https://static.digit.in/6-11-768x768.png 768w, https://static.digit.in/6-11-1536x1536.png 1536w, https://static.digit.in/6-11-2048x2048.png 2048w, https://static.digit.in/6-11-100x100.png 100w, https://static.digit.in/6-11-350x350.png 350w, https://static.digit.in/6-11-788x788.png 788w, https://static.digit.in/6-11-600x600.png 600w, https://static.digit.in/6-11-96x96.png 96w, https://static.digit.in/6-11.png 732w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"632\" height=\"632\"></figure><h2><strong>Ports</strong></h2><p>Connectivity-wise, the Scar 16 does not disappoint. With two USB-A and two USB-C ports (including one Thunderbolt 4), HDMI, audio, and Gigabit Ethernet ports, it’s got you covered. No storage card reader though, but this laptop is all about power.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:311/311;\" src=\"https://static.digit.in/3-11-1024x1024.png\" alt=\"ASUS ROG Strix SCAR 16\" srcset=\"https://static.digit.in/3-11-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://static.digit.in/3-11-300x300.png 300w, https://static.digit.in/3-11-150x150.png 150w, https://static.digit.in/3-11-768x768.png 768w, https://static.digit.in/3-11-1536x1536.png 1536w, https://static.digit.in/3-11-2048x2048.png 2048w, https://static.digit.in/3-11-100x100.png 100w, https://static.digit.in/3-11-350x350.png 350w, https://static.digit.in/3-11-788x788.png 788w, https://static.digit.in/3-11-600x600.png 600w, https://static.digit.in/3-11-96x96.png 96w, https://static.digit.in/3-11.png 732w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"311\" height=\"311\"></figure><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:311/311;\" src=\"https://static.digit.in/2-16-1024x1024.png\" alt=\"ASUS ROG Strix SCAR 16\" srcset=\"https://static.digit.in/2-16-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://static.digit.in/2-16-300x300.png 300w, https://static.digit.in/2-16-150x150.png 150w, https://static.digit.in/2-16-768x768.png 768w, https://static.digit.in/2-16-1536x1536.png 1536w, https://static.digit.in/2-16-2048x2048.png 2048w, https://static.digit.in/2-16-100x100.png 100w, https://static.digit.in/2-16-350x350.png 350w, https://static.digit.in/2-16-788x788.png 788w, https://static.digit.in/2-16-600x600.png 600w, https://static.digit.in/2-16-96x96.png 96w, https://static.digit.in/2-16.png 732w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"311\" height=\"311\"></figure><h2><strong>Keypad and Touchpad</strong></h2><p>The keyboard offers a satisfying experience with a crisp, tactile bottoming action. It’s not mechanical, but it’s quick and comfortable, ideal for gaming. The touchpad is spacious, providing a responsive tracking experience. Gamers will likely opt for a dedicated mouse, and in a pinch, the touchpad also doubles as a Numpad, which adds a neat touch.</p><p><a href=\"https://static.digit.in/5-12.png\"><img src=\"https://static.digit.in/5-12-1024x1024.png\" alt=\"ASUS ROG Strix SCAR 16\" srcset=\"https://static.digit.in/5-12-1024x1024.png 1024w, https://static.digit.in/5-12-300x300.png 300w, https://static.digit.in/5-12-150x150.png 150w, https://static.digit.in/5-12-768x768.png 768w, https://static.digit.in/5-12-1536x1536.png 1536w, https://static.digit.in/5-12-2048x2048.png 2048w, https://static.digit.in/5-12-100x100.png 100w, https://static.digit.in/5-12-350x350.png 350w, https://static.digit.in/5-12-788x788.png 788w, https://static.digit.in/5-12-600x600.png 600w, https://static.digit.in/5-12-96x96.png 96w, https://static.digit.in/5-12.png 732w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1024\" height=\"1024\"></a></p><h2><strong>ASUS ROG Strix SCAR 16 Verdict</strong></h2><p>In conclusion, the ASUS ROG Strix Scar 16 is a game-changer, delivering desktop-level performance in a 16-inch laptop form factor. It’s a powerhouse that keeps up with the Scar legacy, featuring the most potent hardware in a premium chassis with a jaw-dropping display. While the range starts at ₹2,89,990, the variant we reviewed comes in at ₹3,29,990. If you’re serious about gaming and want a show-stopping experience, the SCAR 16 is worth every penny.</p>', 1, '2024-03-04 00:27:38', '2024-03-04 00:27:38'),
